@node Copying filenames
@section Copying filenames

@findex dired-extras-copy-filename-as-kill-sans-extension
@findex dired-extras-copy-filename-as-kill-absolute
@findex dired-extras-copy-filename-as-kill-dwim
@findex dired-extras-image-copy-filename-as-kill-absolute
Dired's built-in @code{dired-copy-filename-as-kill} copies the filename at point, but the format is not always what you need. Four commands cover common variations:

@itemize
@item
@code{dired-extras-copy-filename-as-kill-sans-extension} copies the filename at point without its file extension. This is handy when you need the base name for renaming, referencing, or constructing a related filename.

@item
@code{dired-extras-copy-filename-as-kill-absolute} copies the full absolute path of the marked files (or the file at point). Internally, it passes the prefix argument @samp{(0)} to @code{dired-copy-filename-as-kill}.

@item
@code{dired-extras-copy-filename-as-kill-dwim} adapts its behavior to the current display state. When @code{dired-hide-details-mode} is active, it copies base filenames (without directory components); otherwise, it copies full paths. The filenames are joined with newlines, making them easy to paste into a shell or document.

@item
@code{dired-extras-image-copy-filename-as-kill-absolute} works in Image Dired buffers, copying the absolute path of the marked image file (or the one at point) to the kill ring.
@end itemize

@node File operations
@section File operations

@findex dired-extras-mark-screenshots
@findex dired-extras-do-delete-fast
@findex dired-extras-duplicate-this-file
@findex dired-extras-copy-to-remote-docs-directory
Several commands streamline common file operations:

@itemize
@item
@code{dired-extras-mark-screenshots} marks all files matching the macOS screenshot naming pattern (@samp{Screenshot YYYY-MM-DD at HH.MM.SS.png}). This is useful for quickly selecting screenshots for bulk operations such as moving, renaming, or deleting.

@item
@code{dired-extras-do-delete-fast} deletes marked files (or the file at point) without moving them to the system trash. It temporarily overrides @code{system-move-file-to-trash} before calling @code{dired-do-delete}. Use this when deleting large numbers of files where the overhead of the trash utility is unwanted.

@item
@code{dired-extras-duplicate-this-file} creates a copy of the file at point in the same directory, appending @samp{[N]} before the extension where N is the first available integer (e.g., @samp{report.pdf} becomes @samp{report[1].pdf}). The Dired buffer is reverted afterward to show the new file.

@item
@code{dired-extras-copy-to-remote-docs-directory} copies marked files to a remote server (@samp{stafforini.com/docs}) via @samp{scp} and copies the public URL of the last file to the kill ring. This command contains hardcoded server details and requires appropriate SSH configuration.
@end itemize

@node Navigation and sorting
@section Navigation and sorting

@findex dired-extras-up-directory-reuse
@findex dired-extras-sort-toggle-dwim
Two commands improve Dired navigation:

@itemize
@item
@code{dired-extras-up-directory-reuse} navigates to the parent directory by calling @code{find-alternate-file} with @samp{".."}, reusing the current Dired buffer instead of opening a new one. This keeps the buffer list clean when browsing directory trees.

@item
@code{dired-extras-sort-toggle-dwim} toggles the sorting method (typically between name and date) and refreshes the buffer. If point is on the first file when sorting is toggled, it remains on the first file afterward; otherwise, it follows the file that was at point. With a prefix argument, it calls @code{dired-sort-toggle-or-edit} to let you edit the listing switches directly.
@end itemize

@node Image Dired integration
@section Image Dired integration

@findex dired-extras-image-dired-current-directory
@findex dired-extras-copy-image
Two commands integrate Dired with image viewing:

@itemize
@item
@code{dired-extras-image-dired-current-directory} opens all images in the current Dired directory in Image Dired, calling @code{image-dired-show-all-from-dir}.

@item
@code{dired-extras-copy-image} copies the image in the current @samp{image-mode} buffer to the system clipboard using macOS AppleScript. It sets the clipboard to the POSIX file path of the current buffer. This is macOS-specific.
@end itemize

@node Hide details
@section Hide details

@findex dired-extras-hide-details-mode-enhanced
The command @code{dired-extras-hide-details-mode-enhanced} toggles both @code{dired-hide-details-mode} and @code{dired-omit-mode} simultaneously. This provides a consistent ``clean'' and ``full'' view: in clean mode, file details and omitted files (such as dotfiles) are both hidden; in full mode, everything is visible.

It accepts an optional ARG following the standard toggle convention: when called interactively it toggles, a positive number enables the clean view, and a negative number disables it.

@node Transient menus
@chapter Transient menus

@findex dired-extras-dispatch
The command @code{dired-extras-dispatch} opens a transient menu providing quick access to frequently used directories. The menu is organized into columns:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Dired folders}: personal directories such as bibliography, dotfiles, Emacs config, notes, downloads, repos, and various library locations.
@item
@strong{Music}: subdirectories for classical, popular, tango, and unsorted music.
@item
@strong{Special}: context-sensitive entries like the file at point, root, home, and the current buffer's directory (via @code{dired-jump}).
@item
@strong{Tlon: Google Drive} and @strong{Tlon: Dropbox}: project-specific directories for various Tlon publications and team members.
@end itemize

Directory paths are drawn from variables defined in the @samp{paths} package.

