@node Quiet deletion cleanup
@section Quiet deletion cleanup

@findex dired-extras-clean-up-after-deletion-quietly
@findex dired-extras-y-or-n-p-just-yes
When Dired deletes a file, it may prompt to kill the associated buffer. The function @code{dired-extras-clean-up-after-deletion-quietly} is installed as @samp{:around} advice on @code{dired-clean-up-after-deletion} to suppress these prompts. It temporarily wraps @code{y-or-n-p} with @code{dired-extras-y-or-n-p-just-yes}, which returns @code{t} for any prompt starting with ``Kill Dired buffer'' or ``Kill buffer of'', and delegates to the original function otherwise.

@node Gnus Dired patch
@section Gnus Dired patch

@findex gnus-dired-mail-buffers
The function @code{gnus-dired-mail-buffers} (from @samp{gnus-dired}) is patched via @samp{el-patch} to use @code{derived-mode-p} instead of checking for an exact major mode match. The original implementation only recognizes buffers in @code{mail-mode} or those returned by @code{message-buffers}, which means @code{mu4e-compose-mode} and other derived mail modes are not detected. The patch makes @code{gnus-dired-attach} work correctly from any mail composition buffer that derives from @code{mail-mode}.

